employment welding airplanes or filing paperwork, while weak labor laws impoverished suburbanites who mowed lawns, built houses, scrubbed kitchen floors, and stocked supermarket shelves. Federal mortgage programs helped some families buy orderly single-family homes and enter the middle class but also underwrote landlord efforts to cram poor families into suburban attics, basements, and sheds. Keogh explores how policymakers ignored suburban inequality, addressing housing segregation between cities and suburbs rather than suburbanites’ demands for decent jobs, housing, and schools. By turning our attention to the suburban poor, Keogh reveals poverty wasn’t just an urban problem but a suburban one, too. In Levittown’s Shadow deepens our understanding of suburbia’s history—and points us toward more effective ways to combat poverty today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDiscrimination in housingzNew York (State)zLong IslandxHistoryy20th century. 0aEconomic assistance, DomesticzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEqualityxEconomic aspectszNew York (State)zLong Island. 0aPoorzNew York (State)zLong IslandxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aPovertyzNew York (State)zLong Island. 0aSuburbszNew York (State)zLong IslandxEconomic conditionsy20th century. 0aSuburbszNew York (State)zLong IslandxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  apoverty, urban history, Long Island, New York, segregation, suburb, exploitation, exclusion, welfare state.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079732940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226827742423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226827742/original  a978-3-11-079732-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles